    •  Increase Oxygen Intake: Practice deep breathing exercises or use portable oxygen devices.

"sugar_advice_3" : "If you have Type 1 Diabetes, here are some daily recommendations:
1. Blood Sugar Monitoring: Check your blood sugar multiple times daily.
2. Insulin Therapy: Take your insulin injections on schedule, and understand how it works.
3. Diet Management: Count carbohydrates and choose low-GI foods.
4. Exercise: Engage in regular aerobic exercise; monitor your blood sugar before and after.
5. Emergency Preparation: Carry candy or glucose tablets with you, and inform family and friends how to handle low blood sugar.

If you have Type 2 Diabetes, here are some daily recommendations:
1. Blood Sugar Monitoring: Regularly check your blood sugar, especially when adjusting diet, exercise, or medication.
2. Diet Management: Eat a balanced diet, reduce sugar and refined carbs, and increase high-fiber foods.
3. Exercise: Aim for at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic exercise per week, combined with strength training.
4. Medication: Take your diabetes medication on schedule and have regular check-ups.
5. Weight Management: Aim to lose 5-10% of your body weight through healthy eating and exercise.
6. Stress Management: Practice relaxation techniques like meditation, deep breathing, or yoga.
For both Type 1 and Type 2 Diabetes, it’s crucial to regularly see your doctor, have health screenings, and educate yourself about diabetes."

"rate_statement_info" : "Thank you for choosing our app. To better understand and manage your heart health, please carefully read the following information:

I. Heart Rate Range

  1. Resting Heart Rate:
    a.Bradycardia (Low Heart Rate): Below 60 bpm.
    b.Normal Range: 60-100 bpm (beats per minute).
    c.Tachycardia (High Heart Rate): Above 100 bpm.

  2. Light Activity Heart Rate:
    a.Low Heart Rate: Below 100 bpm.
    b.Normal Range: 100-130 bpm.
    c.High Heart Rate: Above 130 bpm.

  3. Moderate Activity/Exercise Heart Rate:
    a.Low Heart Rate: Below 130 bpm.
    b.Normal Range: 130-150 bpm.
    c.High Heart Rate: Above 150 bpm.

  4. High-Intensity Exercise Heart Rate:
    a.Low Heart Rate: Below 150 bpm.
    b.Normal Range: 150-185 bpm.
    c.High Heart Rate: Above 185 bpm.

II. Heart Rate Measurement Principle
Our app uses photoplethysmography (PPG) to monitor heart rate through your smartphone's camera and flashlight. Users place their finger on the camera, which detects blood flow variations. By analyzing these changes, the app calculates your heart rate.

III. Disclaimer
Please note:
    •  All data and analyses provided by the app are for reference only and should not be used as a basis for medical diagnosis and treatment.
    •  If you have heart-related health concerns, be sure to consult medical professionals.
    •  We are not responsible for any consequences arising from the use of this app, including but not limited to health issues or inaccurate measurements.

IV. Official Information Sources
For more information on cardiovascular health and professional advice, please visit:"
